VALUES
(1, 20, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'she is the daughter of my father, but not the daughter of my mother;', 33, 101, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Daughter''', 'בַּת (bat, H1323) - daughter, girl. This term underscores the importance of lineage and inheritance in biblical narratives, particularly concerning roles within family and society.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1323", "description": "Hebrew word for daughter, signifying familial connections."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'she became my wife.', 106, 125, 'question', 'Marriage and Identity', 'What does it mean for Sarah to be both sister and wife in the context of covenant relationships? How does this duality reflect on God''s design for marriage and family?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'when God caused me to wander from my father’s house', 21, 72, 'connection', 'Divine Guidance in Wandering', 'This phrase echoes Abraham''s journey and the theme of divine guidance through uncertainty. A parallel can be drawn to Genesis 12:1, where God commands Abraham to leave his country and family. The significance lies in understanding how God''s leading often involves leaving familiar places to fulfill His promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1", "description": "God''s call for Abraham to leave his homeland"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'This is thy kindness which thou shalt shew unto me', 96, 146, 'theology', 'The Nature of Kindness', 'This request reflects the importance of kindness in relationships, particularly in marriage. Many scholars believe this indicates an early understanding of mutual respect and support between spouses, which aligns with New Testament teachings on love and kindness, as seen in Ephesians 5:25-28.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 5:25-28", "description": "Paul''s teaching on love and kindness in marriage"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'at every place whither we shall come', 148, 184, 'question', 'Faith in Journey', 'What does it mean for us to acknowledge God''s presence and protection in every place we go? How does this awareness shape our decisions and interactions with others as we journey through life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'took sheep, and oxen, and menservants, and womenservants', 14, 70, 'connection', 'Abimelech''s Generosity', 'Abimelech''s act of giving livestock and servants to Abraham reflects a broader theme of hospitality and restitution found in Scripture. For instance, in Exodus 22:1, the principle of restitution is laid out, indicating that if someone steals an animal, they must repay it with additional animals. This connection highlights the idea that God often uses foreign kings to honor His chosen people, showing His sovereignty over all nations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 22:1", "description": "Explains the principle of restitution in the law."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 21:1", "description": "Indicates that the heart of the king is in the hand of the Lord."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'gave them unto Abraham', 76, 98, 'theology', 'God''s Provision', 'This verse illustrates the theological concept of God''s provision for His people. Many scholars believe that the gifts given to Abraham by Abimelech serve as evidence of God''s favor and protection over Abraham, even amidst his failures. This reflects the broader biblical narrative where God provides for His people, often in surprising ways, reminding believers of His faithfulness.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s provision in the lives of the patriarchs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'restored him Sarah his wife', 104, 131, 'question', 'Understanding Restoration', 'What does the restoration of Sarah to Abraham signify in terms of covenant relationships? As Sarah is returned to Abraham, it prompts reflection on the nature of restoration in our own lives. How does God seek to restore broken relationships in your life, and what steps are necessary for that restoration to take place?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Behold, my land is before thee: dwell where it pleaseth thee.', 20, 81, 'connection', 'Divine Provision', 'Abimelech''s offer to Abraham echoes the promise of land made to Abraham in Genesis 12:7, where God tells him, ''To your offspring I will give this land.'' This connection highlights the theme of God providing for His chosen ones, even through unexpected means, as Abimelech was not part of the covenant community yet facilitated God''s plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:7", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham regarding land."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'my land is before thee: dwell where it pleaseth thee.', 28, 81, 'theology', 'Hospitality in Scripture', 'This verse reflects the importance of hospitality in biblical theology. Many scholars believe that Abimelech''s offer symbolizes the welcoming nature of God''s creation, where land is a resource for community and fellowship. The act of offering land can be seen as an invitation to live in peace and security, reminiscent of Jesus'' teachings on hospitality.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of hospitality in the Bible."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'dwell where it pleaseth thee.', 52, 81, 'question', 'Personal Dwelling', 'What does it mean for you to dwell in a place that pleases you, both physically and spiritually? How does this verse challenge you to consider where God has placed you and how you can thrive in that environment?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Behold, my land is before thee:', 20, 51, 'greek', 'Land and Authority', 'אֶרֶץ (erets, H776) - land, earth, ground. The term signifies not just physical territory but also the authority and responsibility that comes with it. Abimelech''s declaration emphasizes the significance of land as a gift from God, which carries both privilege and obligation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H776", "description": "Strong''s number for ''land'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'a thousand pieces of silver', 57, 84, 'connection', 'Value of Silver in Scriptures', 'The mention of ''a thousand pieces of silver'' can be cross-referenced with Genesis 23:15, where Abraham negotiates for a burial site, emphasizing the significance of silver as a form of wealth and transaction in biblical times. This connection illustrates the gravity of Abimelech''s gesture towards Sarah and Abraham, highlighting both his acknowledgment of her value and the seriousness of the situation. The use of silver also symbolizes purity and redemption.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 23:15", "description": "Abraham''s negotiation for the cave of Machpelah"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'a covering of the eyes', 108, 130, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Covering', 'The phrase ''a covering of the eyes'' suggests a protective role, indicating that Abraham''s presence is meant to shield Sarah from potential harm or shame. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological concept of protection and honor within marriage, as seen in Ephesians 5:25-29, which speaks to the husband''s duty to care for and protect his wife. This illustrates the sacredness of marital relationships in Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 5:25-29", "description": "Instructions on marital love and protection"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'thus she was reproved', 181, 202, 'question', 'Understanding Reproof', 'What does it mean for Sarah to be ''reproved'' in this context? Consider how this reproof might reflect on her understanding of her identity and role within the covenant community. How can we apply the concept of reproof in our lives today, particularly in the context of relationships that challenge our faith and integrity?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'So Abraham prayed unto God:', 0, 27, 'connection', 'Prayer''s Role in Healing', 'This phrase highlights the power of prayer, resonating with James 5:16, which states, ''The prayer of a righteous person is powerful and effective.'' This connection emphasizes the belief that intercession can lead to divine intervention, as seen in Abraham''s act of praying for Abimelech, which resulted in healing.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 5:16", "description": "Illustrates the efficacy of prayer in bringing about healing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and God healed Abimelech, and his wife, and his maidservants;', 28, 89, 'theology', 'Divine Healing and Restoration', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of God as a healer and restorer. Many scholars believe this reflects God''s grace, demonstrating His willingness to restore not just individuals but entire households. This aligns with the broader biblical theme of restoration following sin or disobedience.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and they bare children.', 90, 113, 'question', 'Significance of Progeny', 'What does the restoration of fertility in Abimelech''s household reveal about God''s covenant promises? Reflect on how this act of healing serves not only as a physical restoration but also signifies hope for the continuation of God''s purposes through the generations.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'the Lord had fast closed up all the wombs of the house of Abimelech', 4, 71, 'connection', 'Divine Intervention', 'This phrase highlights God''s direct involvement in human affairs, paralleling instances like Exodus 23:26, where God promises to bless His people with fertility. It underscores the theme of God''s sovereignty over life and death, as seen in 1 Samuel 1:5-6, where the Lord closes Hannah''s womb, leading to significant redemptive outcomes. Understanding these connections reinforces the belief in God''s active role in fulfilling His promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 23:26", "description": "God''s promise of fertility to His people."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 1:5-6", "description": "The Lord''s control over fertility and its implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'the Lord had fast closed up all the wombs', 4, 45, 'greek', 'Closed Wombs', 'סָגַר (sagar, H5462) - to shut, close, restrain. This Hebrew term emphasizes God''s authority to close or open wombs, illustrating His power over creation and life. It suggests that the act of closing wombs is not merely physical but also a divine decree that can lead to significant theological implications regarding His covenant promises.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5462", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'because of Sarah Abraham’s wife', 73, 104, 'theology', 'Covenantal Significance', 'This passage suggests that God''s actions are directly tied to His covenant with Abraham and Sarah. Many scholars believe it illustrates how God protects His covenant people, ensuring that His promises cannot be thwarted by human actions or decisions. It reflects the broader theological theme of God''s faithfulness and His commitment to fulfill His covenant despite human failings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis Commentary by John Walton", "description": "Insight on God''s covenant faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'the Lord had fast closed up all the wombs', 4, 45, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Actions', 'What does it mean for God to close wombs in the context of His promises to Abraham and Sarah? How does this event shape our understanding of God''s sovereignty and intervention in human history?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And the Lord visited Sarah as he had said', 0, 41, 'connection', 'God''s Faithfulness to Promise', 'This phrase echoes God''s faithfulness as seen in Genesis 18:14, where God reassures Abraham that nothing is too hard for Him. The connection highlights the theme of divine intervention and fulfillment of promises, which is central to understanding God''s character throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 18:14", "description": "God reassures Abraham of His power to fulfill promises."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'as he had said', 27, 41, 'theology', 'The Nature of Divine Promises', 'This phrase suggests that God''s statements are not mere words but are assured truths. Many scholars believe this reinforces the doctrine of divine sovereignty, illustrating that God ultimately brings His plans to fruition, which provides believers with hope and assurance in their faith.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'the Lord did unto Sarah as he had spoken', 47, 87, 'greek', 'Divine Action and Fulfillment', 'עָשָׂה (asah, H6213) - to do, make, create. This Hebrew term emphasizes God''s active role in the fulfillment of His promises. It signifies not just a passive acknowledgment but a powerful execution of His will in the lives of His people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6213", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term meaning ''to do''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'the Lord visited Sarah', 4, 26, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Visits', 'What does it mean for the Lord to ''visit'' someone? How does this concept of divine visitation influence your understanding of God''s personal involvement in the lives of His followers?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'For Sarah conceived, and bare Abraham a son in his old age, at the set time of which God had spoken to him.', 0, 107, 'connection', 'Fulfillment of Promise', 'This verse connects to Genesis 17:19, where God promises Abraham that Sarah will bear a son, indicating God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises. Additionally, Hebrews 11:11 highlights Sarah''s faith in this promise, emphasizing the importance of trust in God''s timing. These references illustrate how God''s promises are realized even in seemingly impossible circumstances.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:19", "description": "God''s specific promise to Sarah about bearing a son."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 11:11", "description": "Affirmation of Sarah''s faith in God''s promise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'For Sarah conceived', 0, 19, 'greek', 'Conceived in Faith', 'Although this verse is in Hebrew, the concept of ''conceived'' resonates with the Greek word γεννάω (gennao, G1080) which translates to ''to beget'' or ''to bring forth''. This word emphasizes the miraculous nature of Sarah''s conception, affirming her role in God''s redemptive plan despite her old age.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1080", "description": "Greek term for begetting, reflecting the miraculous conception."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'at the set time of which God had spoken to him.', 60, 107, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Timing', 'This phrase suggests that God operates within a divine timetable, highlighting His sovereignty over human affairs. Many scholars believe this reflects the theological concept of ''kairos''—the right or opportune moment—as opposed to ''chronos'', the sequential time. This distinction reminds believers of the importance of patience and trust in God''s perfect timing.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'in his old age', 44, 58, 'question', 'God''s Power in Weakness', 'What does this miraculous conception in Abraham''s old age teach us about God''s ability to work through human limitations? How can this insight encourage us in our own situations where we feel inadequate or beyond hope?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Isaac', 87, 92, 'greek', 'Hebrew Name Meaning', 'The name ''Isaac'' comes from the Hebrew יִצְחָק (Yitzhak, H3327), which means ''he will laugh.'' This name is significant as it reflects the joy and astonishment of both Abraham and Sarah at the fulfillment of God''s promise to them, particularly given their advanced age. It symbolizes the laughter of disbelief turned into joy, highlighting God''s power to bring life from barrenness.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3327", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew Dictionary"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'And Abraham called the name of his son', 0, 38, 'theology', 'Naming as Authority', 'In biblical times, naming a child was an act of authority and significance. This passage highlights the importance of God’s covenant promise through Isaac. Many scholars believe that the act of naming signifies Abraham''s acceptance of God''s plan and the establishment of a new covenant lineage through Isaac, marking a pivotal moment in salvation history.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of naming in biblical context"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'whom Sarah bare to him', 63, 85, 'connection', 'Fulfillment of God''s Promise', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 18:10, where God promises Abraham that Sarah will bear a son. The fulfillment of this promise is essential in understanding God''s faithfulness and the miraculous nature of Isaac''s birth. It emphasizes that God''s promises come to fruition despite human limitations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 18:10", "description": "God''s promise of Isaac''s birth"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 4:19-21", "description": "Abraham''s faith in God''s promises"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Abraham called the name of his son', 4, 38, 'question', 'What does naming signify?', 'In what ways does the act of naming Isaac reflect Abraham''s faith and obedience to God? How can we apply the significance of names and identity in our own lives, particularly in recognizing the names that God has given us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'And Abraham circumcised his son Isaac being eight days old, as God had commanded him.', 0, 85, 'connection', 'Covenant Significance', 'This act of circumcision is significant as it marks the covenant relationship between God and Abraham''s descendants. It can be cross-referenced with Genesis 17:10-14, where God commands Abraham to circumcise every male among his household, establishing it as a perpetual sign of the covenant. This connection highlights the importance of obedience to God''s commands as foundational to the faith of Abraham and his descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:10-14", "description": "God''s command for circumcision as a sign of the covenant."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'as God had commanded him.', 60, 85, 'theology', 'Obedience to Divine Command', 'This phrase underlines a central tenet in Christian theology: the importance of obedience to God''s commandments. Many scholars believe that Abraham''s immediate compliance illustrates the model of faith and obedience expected from believers. This reflects the broader theological principle that faith is expressed through action, as seen in James 2:17, which states that faith without works is dead.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 2:17", "description": "Faith must be accompanied by works."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'being eight days old', 38, 58, 'question', 'Why Eight Days?', 'Why is the timing of circumcision set at eight days? This specific timing may have implications regarding purity and readiness. Reflecting on this detail, how does it inform our understanding of God''s design and timing in our lives? In what ways might we need to wait for God''s perfect timing in our own spiritual journeys?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'circumcised his son Isaac', 12, 37, 'greek', 'Circumcision in Language', 'מִילָה (milah, H4139) - circumcision, to cut off. This Hebrew term emphasizes the physical act of circumcision as a covenantal obligation. The act signifies not only physical identity but also spiritual belonging within the community of God''s people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4139", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to circumcision."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Abraham was an hundred years old', 4, 36, 'connection', 'Old Age and Promise', 'The mention of Abraham''s age parallels God''s promise to him in Genesis 17:17, where Abraham is incredulous about having a child at such an old age. This connection underscores the miraculous nature of Isaac''s birth and highlights God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His promises, even when circumstances seem impossible.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:17", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham regarding Isaac''s birth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'when his son Isaac was born unto him', 38, 74, 'theology', 'Divine Intervention', 'This verse illustrates a key theological theme of divine intervention in human affairs. Many scholars believe that Isaac''s birth signifies God''s sovereignty in orchestrating events that fulfill His covenant with Abraham, revealing God''s ability to transcend natural limitations. It speaks to the idea of faith in God''s promises, regardless of human impossibility.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on God''s covenant with Abraham."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'when his son Isaac was born unto him', 38, 74, 'question', 'Faith Amidst Doubt', 'What does Isaac''s miraculous birth teach us about trusting God when circumstances appear hopeless? Consider how Abraham''s faith was tested and ultimately rewarded, prompting reflection on how we respond to God''s promises in our own lives.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'an hundred years old', 16, 36, 'greek', 'Aged Wisdom', 'The phrase ''an hundred years old'' can be linked to the Hebrew term מֵאָה (me''ah, H3967) - hundred, symbolizing completeness or fullness. This reflects the fullness of God''s timing in Abraham''s life and serves as a reminder that God''s plans unfold in their own time, often beyond human expectations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3967", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''hundred''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'God hath made me to laugh', 16, 41, 'connection', 'Laughter as Divine Gift', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 126:2, where it states, ''Then our mouth was filled with laughter, and our tongue with shouts of joy.'' Both passages highlight how God’s blessings can evoke joy and laughter. Sarah’s exclamation not only expresses personal joy but also invites others to share in the celebration of God’s miraculous provision, emphasizing the communal aspect of joy in faith.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 126:2", "description": "Connection to communal joy from divine blessing"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'so that all that hear will laugh with me', 43, 83, 'theology', 'The Nature of Blessing', 'This passage suggests that blessings from God are meant to be shared. Many scholars believe that Sarah''s declaration represents a communal response to God''s faithfulness. The joy of one believer can inspire and uplift the community, reflecting the biblical principle that personal blessings are often designed to encourage others in their faith journeys.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'God hath made me to laugh', 16, 41, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Laugh''', 'צָחַק (tsachaq, H6711) - to laugh or rejoice. This Hebrew verb conveys not just laughter but a profound joy often tied to unexpected blessings. Sarah’s use of this word indicates a deep sense of joy and surprise at God''s fulfillment of His promise, highlighting the emotional and spiritual dimensions of her experience.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6711", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'God hath made me to laugh', 16, 41, 'question', 'What does laughter signify?', 'How does the laughter that comes from God''s blessings change your understanding of His promises? In what ways can this joy inspire you to share your faith with others, inviting them into the joy of God’s work in your life?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Who would have said unto Abraham, that Sarah should have given children suck?', 14, 91, 'connection', 'Promise and Fulfillment', 'This phrase echoes God''s earlier promise to Abraham in Genesis 17:19, where He declares that Sarah will bear a son. The incredulity expressed here highlights the miraculous nature of Isaac''s birth, reinforcing the theme of divine intervention in fulfilling promises. This connection illustrates God''s faithfulness despite human doubt.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:19", "description": "God''s promise of Isaac''s birth"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'for I have born him a son in his old age.', 92, 133, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Life Stages', 'This passage suggests that God operates beyond human limitations and societal norms regarding age and fertility. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader theological concept of God''s sovereignty, where He orchestrates events according to His divine plan, thus emphasizing the miraculous nature of life and God''s active role in it.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 21:7", "description": "Commentary on God''s divine timing"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Who would have said unto Abraham, that Sarah should have given children suck?', 14, 91, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Possibilities', 'What does this verse reveal about our own expectations regarding God''s promises? How often do we doubt the possibilities that seem impossible in our lives? Reflecting on Sarah''s astonishment can lead to a deeper understanding of faith and trust in God''s timing and power.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 21, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'the child grew, and was weaned', 4, 34, 'connection', 'Growth and Weaning', 'This phrase connects with Exodus 2:10, where Moses is described as being ''drawn out of the water'' and later raised in Pharaoh''s house. Both narratives highlight significant moments of transition in a child''s life, suggesting a divine purpose in their development. The weaning of Isaac signifies not only physical growth but also the unfolding of God''s promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 2:10", "description": "Moses''s growth parallels Isaac''s weaning"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');